snippet.textDisplay: Archaeologist here! <3 The sculpture is of the Roman emperor Hadrian; Hadrian's lover was a Greek man named Antinous, who drowned while saving Hadrian's life when they were attacked on the Nile (accounts vary as to whether it was alligators or hippo). Emperor Hadrian was actually the first Roman emperor to bring the beard in fashion, since he had acne scars from his youth that he wanted to cover up(as well as pox scars); previous to this time beards were considered barbaric and something only the Gauls (modern day France) and Northerners wore. After the death of Antinous, Hadrian's wife and children were very distraught as he was treated as one of the family (Hadrian's marriage was one of political necessity), and the overwhelming majority of sculpture that we have from this time period is of Antinous since both Hadrian and his wife commissioned so many! :)
